u} $, in $ \mathrm{W\,m^{-2}\,sr^{-1}\,Hz^{-1}} $ at the same central wavelength.

Starting from the foundational definition that spectral radiance is the radiance per unit spectral variable, and invoking the change-of-variables principle between wavelength and frequency grounded in the relation $ 
u = c / \lambda $ with speed of light $ c = 2.99792458 	imes 10^{8}\ \mathrm{m\,s^{-1}} $, derive the conversion and explain the origin and sign of the Jacobian factor for changing variables from wavelength to frequency. Then compute the numerical value of $ L_{
u} $ at $ \lambda = 550\ \mathrm{nm} $ using the provided $ L_{\lambda} $.

Round your final numeric answer for $ L_{
u} $ to four significant figures. Express the final $ L_{
u} $ in $ \mathrm{W\,m^{-2}\,sr^{-1}\,Hz^{-1}} $.
